'''Shooting the gap''' is a term used in [[American football]].<ref>http://www.sportingcharts.com/dictionary/nfl/shooting-the-gap.aspx</ref>  To "shoot the [[Gap (American  football)|gap]]," a [[defensive team|defensive lineman]] will exploit the space between the [[offensive team|offensive linemen]] during a [[pass rush]].<ref>https://books.google.com/books?id=rj41fl3yuxEC&pg=PA50</ref>  The defensive lineman is usually one of the defensive tackles.  The gaps are given different letters depending on their distance from the [[center (football)|center]].  The gaps between the center and the guard are known as the "A gaps", and the gaps between the guard and the tackle are known as the "B gaps". Shooting the gap requires the defensive lineman to turn his shoulders and get past the offensive line into the backfield by any means possible, usually by diving through the gap.  The play is often used during a blitz, as the defense will try to rush past the offensive line in order to get to the [[quarterback]] and cause a [[quarterback sack]].

